There are 12 recorded perlid stoneflies from Luzon Island, Philippines , of which nine are
Neoperla Needham, 1905
and three are
Phanoperla Banks, 1938
(Table 1) (
;
;
;
;
). In a biogeographic perspective, Luzon Island is of great importance to understand the stonefly diversity in the Philippines . It bridges Taiwan to Mindoro-Palawan block, and other oceanic islands of the Philippines such as Marinduque , Romblon , Sibuyan, Panay, Masbate , and Samar . Hypothetically, it can act as a gateway for species migration and colonization as well as a center of speciation due to its varied mountain ranges and inland water bodies.

The specimens were examined using a LEICA EZ4 stereomicroscope. Several images at varying focal points of male terminalia and habitus were taken using Canon EOS 6D Mark II and then stacked using Helicon Focus version 5.3. Aedeagus of each specimen was removed from the male terminalia and artificially everted through the cold maceration technique (

). These were then viewed and studied under OLYMPUS CX21 compound microscope. Consequently, a Dino-Lite eyepiece camera was attached to the microscope to photograph varying focal points of the aedeagus and then stacked using Combine ZP (

). All images were enhanced using Adobe Lightroom and Adobe Photoshop. Terminologies follow 

and 

.

Diagnosis. The aedeagus closely resembles the description of
N. jewetti
having the “smallest spiny protrusions distal and the largest proximal; rest of the everted sac covered with fine spinulets except for the stronger spines near the tip” (
). However, the illustration (
) is slightly different from the specimen at hand although the difference may just be attributed to the eversion of the lobes.

Remarks:
This species has been recorded previously in Southern Luzon (Mt. Makiling, Los Baños) (

). The new record extends its distribution to Central Luzon.

